article.headline: Lawson scores seven in final six minutes
article.linkText: Monarchs, with Lawson on their side, absorb Sting
article.story:
SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) -- The Sacramento Monarchs went into
their Olympic break in a good frame of mind following a comeback
victory over the Charlotte Sting.

Tangela Smith scored 13 points to lead the Monarchs to a 62-61
win Saturday night. Sacramento won't play again until Sept. 1 and
won't hold a practice for 10 days.

"This victory was huge, we were going to think about the
outcome, win or lose, for the next month," Monarchs guard Kara
Lawson said. "This is a big boost."

The Sting (12-12) squandered a nine-point lead in the second
half and fell out of first place in the Eastern Conference.
Charlotte, which plays Sunday at Seattle before starting its break,
trails New York by a half-game.

"We were up nine points, but we had too many breakdowns after
that," Sting forward Allison Feaster said. "We had 18 turnovers
and didn't do a good job defensively down the stretch. We knew
Sacramento was capable of coming back, they have people who play
well down the stretch."

One of them is Lawson, who can be a streaky shooter. She made a
pull-up jumper off a fastbreak to put the Monarchs (12-13) ahead
for good at 60-59 with 2:33 left. It was Sacramento's first lead
since midway through the first half.

"It's something Coach (John Whisenant) has talked to me about,
not going all the way in on the break and pulling up instead,"
Lawson said. "That's actually one of my better shots."

Looking for the winning shot, Charlotte rookie Nicole Powell was
bothered by DeMya Walker and Ticha Penicheiro. She couldn't get a
shot off before the game ended.

"I knew she (Powell) couldn't take me off the dribble and I
wanted to play up on her because she made some 3s in the first
half," Walker said. "They tried to set a screen in the last
seconds and Ticha went for broke and pulled it off."

Sacramento, fighting to make the Western Conference playoffs,
maintained its dominance over Charlotte. The Sting are 1-7 at Arco
Arena and haven't won there since July 10, 1998.

"We thought we were the better team, but we didn't get the
victory," Feaster said.

Walker had 11 points for the Monarchs, and Lawson scored 10.
Olympian Yolanda Griffith had a sub-par game, finishing with eight
points and five rebounds. Ruthie Bolton had nine points.

Feaster had 16 points, and Andrea Stinson added 15 for the
Sting, who had their two-game winning streak snapped. Powell scored
11 points, all in the first half.

Dawn Staley, who will also play in the Olympics, had nine points
and eight assists for Charlotte. Powell made three 3-pointers and
scored 11 points.
